<worksheet label="ws-PA-trig-inverse">
  <exploration xml:id="PA-trig-inverse">
    <introduction>
      <p>
			Consider the plot of the standard cosine function in <xref ref="F-inverse-trig-PA-cos">Figure</xref> along with the emphasized portion of the graph on <m>[0,\pi]</m>.
		</p>
      <figure xml:id="F-inverse-trig-PA-cos">
        <caption>The cosine function on <m>[-\frac{5\pi}{2},\frac{5\pi}{2}]</m> with the portion on <m>[0,\pi]</m> emphasized.</caption>
        <image source="images/inverse-trig-PA-cosine"/>
      </figure>
      <p>
			Let <m>g</m> be the function whose domain is <m>0 \le t \le \pi</m> and whose outputs are determined by the rule <m>g(t) = \cos(t)</m>.  <em>Note well</em>: <m>g</m> is defined in terms of the cosine function, but because it has a different domain, it is <em>not</em> the cosine function.
		</p>
      <p/>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-trig-inverse-task-0">
      <statement>
        <p>
		            What is the domain of <m>g</m>?
		          </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-trig-inverse-task-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
		            What is the range of <m>g</m>?
		          </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-trig-inverse-task-2">
      <statement>
        <p>
		            Does <m>g</m> pass the horizontal line test?
		            Why or why not?
		          </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-trig-inverse-task-3">
      <statement>
        <p>
		            Explain why <m>g</m> has an inverse function,
		            <m>g^{-1}</m>, and state the domain and range of <m>g^{-1}</m>.
		          </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-trig-inverse-task-4">
      <statement>
        <p>
		            We know that <m>g(\frac{\pi}{4}) = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m>.
		            What is the exact value of <m>g^{-1}(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})</m>?
		            How about the exact value of <m>g^{-1}(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})</m>?
		          </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-trig-inverse-task-5">
      <statement>
        <p>
		            Determine the exact values of <m>g^{-1}(-\frac{1}{2})</m>,
		            <m>g^{-1}(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})</m>,
		            <m>g^{-1}(0)</m>, and <m>g^{-1}(-1)</m>.
		            Use proper notation to label your results.
		          </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
  </exploration>
</worksheet>
